 as head of strategy and ecommerce for coca cola’s north america group the yearold mcgurk said it was a former colleague’s untimely death several years ago that made her realize she had creative aspirations beyond her day job and parenthood “you never really know when your time’s going to be up” she noted “earlier in my life i had dabbled a little in writing so i thought i’d start writing again maybe squeezing it in on plane trips and quiet times late at night”in spite of the requisite rejections from other publishers her efforts paid off when greenleaf book group gave her the thumbsupthe mom of three said flahs classmates may remember her as “smart but a little geeky” because she participated so heavily in speech debate and theater she credits former teachers and coaches deb bendix dorothy sunne and jane gilles for her critical thinking and public speaking skills mcgurk now holds a ba from harvard and both an ma and an mba from stanford while her past resume includes management jobs at deluxe corp the ohio chamber orchestra general mills and stanford for  years she worked for minneapolis management consulting firm mckinsey  co becoming partner before leaving two years ago to join cocacolain between those jobs she founded the alumni factor a college evaluation system that ranks schools on realworld outcomesshe and her husband tom have three children son trey  daughter reagan  and son john patrick mcgurk’s role at coca cola these days involves strategizing and decisionmaking — usually three to four years ahead —  about how to best use resources and maximize markets to drive volume growthonce she decided to start writing fiction her first work was a fan fiction piece that presented an alternative ending to stephanie meyer’s “twilight” series she titled “morning star” the positive feedback she received after posting it on sciencefictionnet and winning the  twific fandom “undiscovered gem” award encouraged her to post her prequel to the series called “rosalie’s revenge” and then start work on “dark hope”paranormal themes and the young adult genre seemed a natural fit to the fan of the harry potter series“i talked to a few writers and kind of approached it as a puzzle” she said “a lot of the career work i do is problem solving big hairy issues  and to be figuring out plot and character is all a big problemsolving exercise” a physician friend advised her on medical issues in the plot while a contact from las vegas gave her tips about the gaming industry“it was really kind of neat to dive into these worlds and go places not everyone has gone” she notedin spite of her past career success she said she’s somewhat daunted to hear reactions to the book and she’s selfcritical of some of her own writing“there’s always the trepidation of putting yourself out there” she said “you have to be prepared for people to hate it as much as you would want them to love it” next up she’s completing two other novels in the “dark hope” series to which the publisher has already committed the next one now being edited is partly set in europe and involves historical artifacts in a nod toward dan brown thrillersthe process also involved research into reallife issues in which mcgurk has made something of a platform human trafficking and child exploitation“i was really shocked to find there really is an active trade in the united states” she said “i had no idea atlanta is one of the biggest places for human trafficking in the us and once you learn about it you can’t turn away it’s such a horrific thing”since then she’s joined the advisory board and speakers’ bureau of norcross georgiabased organization street grace which works to raise awareness of such issues  a portion of revenues from the “dark hope” trilogy will be donated to the nonprofit  in her spare time she likes to run travel with her family and volunteer through her church she only occasionally gets back to minnesota as her parents have moved to arizona  becoming a fulltime writer is probably not in the cards for mcgurk“i really have enjoyed my career in business” she noted “it was never really planned i kind of fell into it but i still enjoy it and it’s now normal to have lots of different careers in your life at the same time people put a lot of pressure on themselves to know what they want to do when they go to school but i think it’s ok to not know to explore or change your mind because you’re discovering something new and fascinating”michelle miron is editor of the forest lake lowdown tags atlanta cocacola mcgurk forest lake area high school harry potter greenleaf book group general mills × post a comment as emoticons smile beam wink sad cool innocent rolleyes whistling lol huh tongue love sleeping yawn unsure angry blink crying ohmy scared sleep sneaky tonguesmile thumbdown thumbup censored happybirthday ban spam offtopic batman ninja pirate alien comment text cancel post comment × report cancel report abuse × watch this discussion stop watching this discussion get an email notification whenever someone contributes to the discussion notifications from this discussion will be disabled cancel start watching stop watching  comments welcome to the discussion log in keep it clean please avoid obscene vulgar lewd racist or sexuallyoriented language please turn off your caps lock dont threaten threats of harming another person will not be tolerated be truthful dont knowingly lie about anyone or anything be nice no racism sexism or any sort of ism that is degrading to another person be proactive use the report link on each comment to let us know of abusive posts share with us wed love to hear eyewitness accounts the history behind an article post a comment watch this discussion stop watching this discussion latest news police begin summer crosswalk enforcement aboat racing maiden voyage akin to baptism under fire viewing lake history from a bicycle seat white bear lake police officer honored at twins game new board member appointed to white bear lake conservation